\chapter{Theoretical Background}

\section{The formation of clouds}
Prerequisites for cloud formation are: moisture, cloud condensation nuclei (CCN) and initial cooling. So in the first place, for precipitation to occur sufficient moisture  in the air is needed to condense out. Although air can be supersaturated with respect to water surfaces are still needed on which condensation can take place. Within a cloud the surface on which droplets form are called cloud condensation nuclei (CCN). Initial cooling  of air with enough moisture and CCN below its dew-point temperature will lead to partial condensation of its water content. An external event causing notable initial cooling is vertical uplift, which can free or forced. Rising density-driven warm air currents or thermals are an example of free convection. Convection is motion or mixing of the air. Air can also be forced to rise, due to an topographical or frontal barrier or due to turbulence. see G Sumner for more information. 1

From: \citet{ManualSynop} Convection in general is mass motion within a fluid resulting in transport and turbulent mixing of the properties of that fluid by vertical movement, in matters of transport of energy (heat), water vapour and momentum. As such, it is one of the three main processes by which energy (heat) can be transported vertically: radiation, conduction, and convection.Meteorologists typically use the term convection to refer to heat transport by the vertical component of the flow associated with an updraft.

\section{Production of precipitation}
The presence of CCNs allows water to condense out given saturated conditions. Water preferentially condenses on the bigger aerosols, as the water vapour pressure is higher on a surface that is more curved. This is called the curvature effect.  Next to size, an important property of aerosols is hygroscopicity. Many aerosols are hygroscopic, meaning able to attract water onto their surfaces, which allows condensation to take place, even in not completely saturated air. A rain drop has a typical size of about 1000 microns (1.0 mm), while a cloud droplet radius is generally about 20 microns. The development of cloud droplets into rain droplets is, however, not only determined by the condensation process. All cloud droplets will be subject to gravity and often collide when moving vertically. Three different terms are used for the collision process depending on the phase of the two particles: coalescene (for liquid on liquid), aggregation (for solid on solid) and accretion (for liquid on solid). The mode of collision may determine the form of the precipitation. In general, coalescene produces rain or drizzl; aggregation, snow; and accretion, ice pellets and ice grains, or hail. Another important mechanism behind rapid growth of cloud particles is called the Bergeron-Findeisen process. When a mixture of supercooled liquid water and ice particles is present in the cloud, differences in water vapour pressure (this is lower for ice than for water) lead to fast evaporation of water and deposition on the ice particles. Therefore, ice particles can grow very efficiently.
Not all clouds generate rainfall, for example when they are too short-lived in order to produce large enough particles. It can also be that clouds are too shallow/ small vertical extent, therefore less vertical motions meaning less cloud droplet growth by collision. Moreover, they can be too high in the atmosphere, where moisture availability is small,  the degree of vertical motion is small (except for convectional clouds with enough vertical development in all layers) and there is a longer pathway for the falling rain droplets (so larger possibility to fall through a layer of unsaturated air). ?! Testing:  Cloud properties are difficult with our data, but general relation with more moisture in air with higher temperature, more aerosols  & shift in position of clouds in the 20th century (climate change).


\section{Conditions for extreme rainfall}

As we currently know the basic ingredients required for precipitation, we focus more on the mechanism behind extreme precipitation. As extreme rain fall is caused by processes of different scales, they are listed here from large- to small-scale.
\subsection{Synoptic conditions}
Large-scale (Grimm and Silva Dias 1995; Gandu and Silva Dias 1998; Aceituno 1989) and mesoscale patterns of convection and precipitation (Velasco and Fritsch 1987) can be modulated by interannual variations such as El Niño–Southern Oscillation (ENSO) and related teleconnections (Hoerling and Kumar 2000).  Meso-α scale (200–2000 km) aspects of extreme precipitation are very often associated with synoptic conditions (Maddox et al. 1972,1982). This can be modulated by intraseasonal variability (Carvalho et al. 2002; Nogués-Paegle and Mo, 1997; Kiladis and Weickmann 1992). Thus, when considering extreme precipitation data it is important to consider what kind of interaction is present between processes of different scales. 2
\subsection{Cyclone intensity}
In the winter season extreme precipitation and wind speed are related to extremes in cyclone intensity In subregions of the North Atlantic. Furthermore, connections are clearly visible between extremes of cyclone intensity and large-scale atmospheric patterns in these subregions, although this does not apply for the summer season. In winter extremes of cyclone intensity are significantly higher in almost all regions, due to a stronger meridional temperature gradient and an increase in lower tropospheric baroclinity. Baroclinicity is a measure of how misaligned the gradient of constant pressure is from the gradient of constant density. 2
