\subsection{Locally induced precipitation}
Topography or local quasi-permanent areas of surface convergence (f.e. along sea-or land-breeze fronts) are factors forcing convection, but mostly not generating precipitation extremes of the same magnitude as convectional storms. However, as the type of fronts can be slow moving or stationary heavy precipitation can accumulate in a fixed area, but only in the few cases when the degree of uplift or the atmospheric moisture content is sufficient.  Organisation of cloud cells into linear bands (f.e. ‘squall lines’ or ‘sea breeze fronts’) or spiral arms (f.e. in Tropical cyclones) are dependent on large-scale dynamic processes or localized convergence of air near the surface.

