\subsection{Cloud types}
The following two types of clouds, distinguished on the way of formation, are associated with extreme precipitation: free convective  and (occluded) frontal clouds. The first type depends on vertical instability (f.e. expressed as CAPE) and moisture availability (f.e. expressed as specific humidity, relative humidity). The type of clouds associated with free convection are cumuliform clouds, who are dependent on the environmental lapse rate (ELR) and the humidity of the air.  The ELR can be such that positive buoyancy persist through a deep layer of the atmosphere, causing convections currents to be active through the layer with speed and magnitude corresponding to the strength of buoyancy. In this example we have an extreme instable atmosphere, while the opposite ELR belongs to an extreme unstable atmosphere. Convectional precipitation, associated with cumulus and cumulonimbus clouds, operate at small and medium scale. They typically form cells of more intense precipitation over areas of about tens to hundreds of square kilometres. These cells have short life times, as the processes which produce them directly (thermal) or indirectly (forced) are generally restricted to times when the isolation is the strongest. Precipitation is mostly produced by the Bergeron-Findeisen process, because of the considerable vertical development of the clouds (therefore exceeding the 0 degrees C isotherm), so that very intense precipitation (sometimes in form of hail or ice pellets) is resultant.  These clouds formed under conditions of high convectional activity and characterized by a large vertical extent, strong differential motion (updraughts and downdraughts), an international environment in which ice and supercooled droplets may exist in close proximity, and where seeding of the lower part of the cloud takes place by ice from above, are capable of producing precipitation of an extremely high intensity at the ground surface. The majority of severe local storms associated with self-perpetuating convectional systems, are characterized by significant hail production.
The second type of clouds are formed at (occluded) frontal slopes. Especially cold fronts, with colder and denser air forcing warmer air to move on top of it , tend to have a much steeper frontal slope. This  leads to a more pronounced cumuliform of originating clouds, with resultant heavier precipitation. Squall-lines (organisation of cells into a line orientated approximately normal to the direction of movement) are related this cloud type, as they are typically in the form of prefrontal throughs ahead of cold fronts at temperate latitude. Frontal clouds can be recognized by their corresponding synoptic settings of low and high pressure areas and temperature fields and resultant wind direction.  OCCLUDED !

\subsection{Internal dynamic processes in clouds}
A single-cell air mass storm is usually short-lived. As entire cloud/shower circulation processes have an inbuilt self-destructing mechanism in which the thermal is replaced by the cold downdraught. Cold downdraught originates from downward frictional drag and its lower temperature due to rapid evaporation of the falling and already cold precipitation (! p. 153/155 Graham). But when  new cells are formed adjacent to thermals, storm building activity can be transferred from one thermal to the next, thereby lengthening the life time of such a storm. Conditional instability of the second kind (instable air which has the condition that it has to rise a certain vertical distance) may serve this self-enhancing and self-perpetuating process in which the short-lived nature of the individual cumuliform elements or towers contribute to a much longer-lived system. This may account for the development of convective complexes of cumulonimbos clouds which can form tropical cyclones. These clouds will possess areas of downdrought and updraught, with similar order of velocities. The contrast in relative velocity highly contributes to their violence and the violence of precipitation they can produce.



